[[Image:Food production per capita.svg|thumb|Food production per person increased since 1961.]] '''Peak wheat''' is the concept that [[agriculture|agricultural]] production, due to its high use of water and energy inputs,<ref>IFDC, World Fertilizer Prices Soar, {{cite web |url=http://www.ifdc.org/i-wfp021908.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509143540/http://www.ifdc.org/i-wfp021908.pdf |archivedate=2008-05-09 |df= }}</ref> is subject to the [[peak oil|same profile as oil]] and other [[fossil fuel]] production.<ref>"Investing In Agriculture - Food, Feed & Fuel", Feb 29th 2008 at http://www.stockhouse.ca/blogs.asp?page=viewblog&blogid=1482</ref><ref>"Could we really run out of food?", Jon Markman, March 6, 2008 at http://articles.moneycentral.msn.com/Investing/SuperModels/CouldWeReallyRunOutOfFood.aspx</ref><ref>Andrew McKillop (2006-12-13). "Peak Natural Gas is On the Way"</ref> The central tenet is that a point is reached, the "peak", beyond which agricultural production plateaus and does not grow any further,<ref>Agcapita Farmland Investment Partnership - Peak oil v. Peak Wheat, July 1, 2008, {{cite web |url=http://www.farmlandinvestmentpartnership.com/pdfs/Agcapita_Newsletter_-_July_1_2008.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-07-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320104129/http://www.farmlandinvestmentpartnership.com/pdfs/Agcapita_Newsletter_-_July_1_2008.pdf |archivedate=2009-03-20 |df= }}</ref> and may even go into permanent decline.
Based on current [[supply and demand]] factors for agricultural [[commodities]] (e.g. changing diets in the [[emerging economies]], [[biofuels]], declining acreage under irrigation, growing [[world population|global population]], stagnant [[agricultural productivity]] growth{{citation needed|date=February 2011}}), some commentators are predicting a long-term annual production shortfall of around 2% which, based on the highly inelastic [[demand curve]] for food crops, could lead to sustained price increases in excess of 10% a year - sufficient to double crop prices in seven years.<ref>Globe Investor at http://www.globeinvestor.com/servlet/WireFeedRedirect?cf=GlobeInvestor/config&date=20080408&archive=nlk&slug=00011064</ref><ref>Credit Suisse First Boston, Higher Agricultural Prices: Opportunities and Risks, November 2007</ref><ref>Food Production May Have to Double by 2030 - Western Spectator {{cite web |url=http://westernspectator.com/?p=272 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-10-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003215717/http://westernspectator.com/?p=272 |archivedate=2009-10-03 |df= }}</ref>
According to the [[World Resources Institute]], global per capita food production has been increasing substantially for the past several decades.<ref>[http://earthtrends.wri.org/searchable_db/results.php?years=1961-1961,1962-1962,1963-1963,1964-1964,1965-1965,1966-1966,1967-1967,1968-1968,1969-1969,1970-1970,1971-1971,1972-1972,1973-1973,1974-1974,1975-1975,1976-1976,1977-1977,1978-1978,1979-1979,1980-1980,1981-1981,1982-1982,1983-1983,1984-1984,1985-1985,1986-1986,1987-1987,1988-1988,1989-1989,1990-1990,1991-1991,1992-1992,1993-1993,1994-1994,1995-1995,1996-1996,1997-1997,1998-1998,1999-1999,2000-2000,2001-2001,2002-2002,2003-2003,2004-2004,2005-2005&variable_ID=180&theme=8&cID=&ccID=0 Agriculture and Food — Agricultural Production Indices: Food production per capita index] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722075753/http://earthtrends.wri.org/searchable_db/results.php?years=1961-1961,1962-1962,1963-1963,1964-1964,1965-1965,1966-1966,1967-1967,1968-1968,1969-1969,1970-1970,1971-1971,1972-1972,1973-1973,1974-1974,1975-1975,1976-1976,1977-1977,1978-1978,1979-1979,1980-1980,1981-1981,1982-1982,1983-1983,1984-1984,1985-1985,1986-1986,1987-1987,1988-1988,1989-1989,1990-1990,1991-1991,1992-1992,1993-1993,1994-1994,1995-1995,1996-1996,1997-1997,1998-1998,1999-1999,2000-2000,2001-2001,2002-2002,2003-2003,2004-2004,2005-2005&variable_ID=180&theme=8&cID=&ccID=0 |date=2009-07-22 }}, World Resources Institute</ref>
==China== {{further|Peak water}} Water is a necessary [[intermediate good|input]] for food production. Two billion people face acute water shortage this century as Himalayan glaciers melt.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.indianmuslims.info/news/2008/feb/06/two_billion_face_water_famine_himalayan_glaciers_melt.html |title = Two billion face water famine as Himalayan glaciers melt |publisher = Indian Muslim News and Information |author = Joydeep Gupta |date = 2008-02-06 |accessdate = 2009-02-07 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090402131304/http://www.indianmuslims.info/news/2008/feb/06/two_billion_face_water_famine_himalayan_glaciers_melt.html |archivedate = 2009-04-02 |df = }}</ref> Water shortages in China have helped lower the wheat harvest from its peak of 123 million tons in 1997 to below 100 million tons in recent years{{when|date=October 2014}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/HG21Df01.html |title=India grows a grain crisis |author=Raja M |publisher=Asia Times Online |date=2006-07-21 |accessdate=2009-02-07 }}</ref> Of China's 617 cities, 300 are facing water shortages. In many, these shortfalls can be filled only by diverting water from agriculture. Farmers cannot compete economically with industry for water in China.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldwatch.org/node/1621 |title=China's Water Shortage Could Shake World Grain Markets |author=Lester R. Brown and Brian Halweil |publisher=Worldwatch Institute |year=1998 |accessdate=2009-02-07 }}</ref> China is developing a grain deficit even with the over-pumping of its aquifers. Grain production in China has been said to have peaked in 1998 at 392 million tons, falling below 350 million tons in 2000, 2001, and 2002, although such was 571 million tons in 2011 after eight consecutive years of increase from 2003 to 2011.<ref name=ChinaDaily>{{cite web |url=http://europe.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2011-12/27/content_14334860.htm |title=China stresses stable grain production |publisher=China Daily |author=Xinhua |date=2011-12-27 |accessdate=2012-04-07 }}</ref> The annual deficits have been filled by drawing down the country's extensive grain reserves, and by reliance on the world grain market.<ref name=Brown2002>{{cite web |url=http://www.greatlakesdirectory.org/zarticles/080902_water_shortages.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070704120613/http://www.greatlakesdirectory.org/zarticles/080902_water_shortages.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2007-07-04 |title=Water deficits growing in many countries - Water Shortages May Cause Food Shortages |publisher=Great Lakes Directory |author=Lester R. Brown |date=2002-08-09 |accessdate=2009-02-07 }}</ref> Some predict that China will soon become the world's largest importer of grain.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.theglobalist.com/StoryId.aspx?StoryId=3827 |title = China's Shrinking Grain Harvest |author = Lester Brown |publisher = [[The Globalist]] |date = 2004-03-12 |accessdate = 2009-02-07 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090404044638/http://www.theglobalist.com/StoryId.aspx?StoryId=3827 |archivedate = 2009-04-04 |df = }}</ref>
Figures from the U.S. Department of Agriculture ([[USDA]]) contradict many claims that the country's wheat supply is unstable. According to USDA, in 2014 China imported 1.5 billion tonnes (GT) of wheat, and had relatively small exports of 1 GT. However, China ''produced'' 126 GT of wheat in 2014, according to the same source. For comparison, Egypt was 2014's largest importer, with imports of 10.7 GT. If China had imported more than Egypt, it still would have produced almost 10 times more wheat than it imported, while in fact it produced more than 100 times more.<ref name=CN2014IM>{{cite web|title=China Wheat Production by Year|url=http://www.indexmundi.com/agriculture/?country=cn&commodity=wheat|website=Index Mundi|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>
==Russia, Ukraine and Kazakhstan== Russia, Ukraine and Kazakhstan have restricted exports and levied tariffs on wheat. Higher prices are not meeting any opposition from desperate buyers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.moneycentral.msn.com/Investing/SuperModels/CouldWeReallyRunOutOfFood.aspx |title=Could we really run out of food? |publisher=[[MSN]] Money |author=Jon Markman |date=2008-03-06 |accessdate= }}</ref>
